explanation:
OS_GLOBAL_ERROR_NAME_TABLE / OS_IMPL_ERROR_NAME_TABLE — the global error-name tables referenced by Error in the function. You must inspect their definitions/initializers to determine the type and provenance of the Name fields (e.g. whether they are null‑terminated C strings or binary buffers) and to check whether memcmp is used anywhere in the table initialization or accessors.

OS_ErrorTable_Entry_t — the struct/type of table entries. Its definition reveals the type of the Name member (char * vs char[] vs non-string blob) and whether Name is guaranteed to be null‑terminated; this is essential to decide whether any comparison of Name would be a null‑terminated string comparison.

os_err_name_t — the type of *err_name (destination buffer). You need its concrete definition (typically an array type and size) to verify correct sizing/termination and whether any uses could trigger string comparisons that should not use memcmp.

OS_ERROR_NAME_LENGTH — the macro/constant used for buffer sizing and the final termination index. Its value is required to reason about buffer lengths and whether string operations here or elsewhere are treating values as null‑terminated strings (relevant to the memcmp rule).

OS_CHECK_POINTER — the pointer‑check macro/function invoked at the top. Its implementation must be examined to ensure it does not internally use memcmp on null‑terminated strings (or otherwise perform forbidden string comparisons), and to confirm it does not alter pointer semantics relevant to the rule.

strncpy / snprintf — the standard library routines called here. Their prototypes/semantics are needed to confirm these functions are used properly (they are not memcmp) and to ensure no hidden use of memcmp is involved via wrappers in this build.

memcmp — include this symbol to detect whether memcmp is used anywhere reachable (directly in this function, in macros like OS_CHECK_POINTER, or in table initializers/accessors) to compare values that are null‑terminated strings. The MISRA rule is violated only if memcmp is used to compare null‑terminated strings, so locating all uses of memcmp in the symbols above is required.
